<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">An indivisible stochastic process represents an alternat=
ive approach
in which one avoids making the Markov approximation but instead works
with <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">equivalence classes</em> of non=
-Markovian processes. In detail,
one considers the entire equivalence class of non-Markovian stochastic
processes that may differ in their higher-order conditional probabilities
but share the same first-order conditional probabilities <math alttext=3D"p=
\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j,t_{0}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unpars=
ed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p4.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mrow=
><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo fence=3D"false"=
 rspace=3D"0.167em" stretchy=3D"false">|</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>=
t</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">p\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j,t_{0}}}\right)</=
annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_p start_O=
PEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_i , italic_t | italic_j , italic_t start_=
POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></mat=
h>
defined in (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v=
3#S2.E1" title=3D"In 2.1 Basic definitions =E2=80=A3 2 Indivisible Stochast=
ic Processes =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">1</span></a>). As will
be shown in the work ahead, these first-order conditional probabilities
will be enough to give agreement with all the empirical predictions
of quantum theory.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: no=
ne;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">To the extent that quantum theory is empirically adequat=
e, the higher-order
conditional probabilities are then unobservable in experiments and
will be left unspecified in this paper. In particular, probabilities
assigned to <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">whole trajectories</em>,=
 as constructed from higher-order
conditional probabilities in the sense of (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"htt=
ps://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S2.E10" title=3D"In 2.2 Markovian and non-=
Markovian stochastic processes =E2=80=A3 2 Indivisible Stochastic Processes=
 =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text l=
tx_ref_tag">10</span></a>),
are then left unspecified as well. The higher-order conditional probabiliti=
es
of an indivisible stochastic process could, in principle, vary contingently
from one set of instantiations or runs of the process to another.
Whether there exists some theoretical principle that picks out one
set of higher-order or whole-trajectory probabilities from all the
various possibilities is a question that will be left to future work.</p><b=
utton class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for pr=
eceding element</button>
</div>
