<p class=3D"ltx_p">Looking at all these results, one notices a striking res=
emblance to
mathematical objects and formulas that are familiar from textbook
quantum theory.<span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote8">=
<sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">8</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">8</sup><span class=3D=
"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">8</span>For pedagogical treatments of quantum theory=
, see the textbooks by
Griffiths and Schroeter (2018); Townsend (2012); Shankar (1994); Sakurai
and Napolitano (2010); and Schumacher and Westmoreland (2010).</span></span=
></span> Specifically, one sees that <math alttext=3D"\Theta\mathopen{}\mat=
hclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal"=
>=CE=98</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false"=
>=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encodin=
g=3D"application/x-tex">\Theta\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\=
right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=
=CE=98 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</=
annotation></semantics></math> plays the
role of a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">time-evolution operator</e=
m>, <math alttext=3D"\rho\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"=
ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.m2"><semantics><mrow>=
<mi>=CF=81</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)=
</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\rho\mathopen{}\math=
close{{\left(t}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-l=
lamapun">italic_=CF=81 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t end_CLOSE=
 )</annotation></semantics></math>
is a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">density matrix,</em> <math altt=
ext=3D"\Psi\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unpar=
