<p class=3D"ltx_p">The system=E2=80=99s transition matrix <math alttext=3D"=
\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_mat=
h_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p4.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi mat=
hvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo=
 stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\le=
ft(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x=
-llamapun">roman_=CE=93 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=
=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>
is then said to be a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">unistochastic m=
atrix</em>. That is, a unistochastic
matrix is a square matrix whose individual entries are the modulus-squares
of the corresponding entries of a unitary matrix.</p><button class=3D"sr-on=
ly button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</but=
ton>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS4.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Unistochastic matrices were first introduced in 1954 by =
Horn (1954)
, who originally called them =E2=80=98ortho-stochastic
matrices.=E2=80=99 The modern term =E2=80=98unistochastic
matrix=E2=80=99 was introduced by Thompson in 1989 (Thompson
1989; Nylen, Tam, Uhlig 1993).
The term <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">orthostochastic matrix</em>=
 now refers to a square matrix
whose entries are the modulus-squares of the corresponding entries
of a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">real orthogonal</em> matrix.</p=
><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for=
 preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS4.p6">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Every orthostochastic matrix is unistochastic. Important=
ly, however,
the reverse is not generally true, meaning that the complex numbers
generically play a necessary role in formulating a unistochastic transition
matrix <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\=
right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p6.m1">=
<semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow=
><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow>=
</mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\m=
athopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=93 start_OPEN end_OPEN start_C=
LOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math> in =
terms of a unitary
time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\le=
ftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3=
.SS4.p6.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t=
</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo=
></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{=
\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"applicatio=
n/x-llamapun">italic_U start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90=
 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>. Even when
the complex numbers are not strictly necessary for writing down a
unitary time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\l=
eft(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" =
id=3D"S3.SS4.p6.m3"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</=
mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><=
mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mat=
hclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-llamapun">italic_U start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =
=E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>,
such as if the time-evolution operator can be taken to be real and
orthogonal, it is still very convenient to employ the complex numbers
for a given Hilbert-space representation, so that one can take advantage
of the many useful constructs that show up in standard treatments
of quantum theory, like spectral decompositions and self-adjoint symmetry
generators.<span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote10"><su=
p class=3D"ltx_note_mark">10</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span clas=
s=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">10</sup><span class=3D"=
ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">10</span>Intriguingly, time-reversal operators includ=
e a complex-conjugation
operator <math alttext=3D"K" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"fo=
otnote10.m1"><semantics><mi>K</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex=
">K</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_K</a=
nnotation></semantics></math> that <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">a=
nticommutes</em> with <math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inl=
ine" id=3D"footnote10.m2"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appl=
ication/x-tex">i</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun=
">italic_i</annotation></semantics></math>, meaning that <math alttext=3D"K=
i=3D-iK" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote10.m3"><semant=
ics><mrow><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><=
mi>i</mi></mrow><mo>=3D</mo><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo lsp=
ace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">Ki=3D-iK</annotation><annotation en=
coding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_K italic_i =3D - italic_i italic_K=
</annotation></semantics></math>,
so the three mathematical objects <math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx_Math" di=
splay=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote10.m4"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation enco=
ding=3D"application/x-tex">i</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"applicatio=
n/x-llamapun">italic_i</annotation></semantics></math>, <math alttext=3D"K"=
 class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote10.m5"><semantics><mi>=
K</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">K</annotation><annotation =
encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_K</annotation></semantics></math=
>, and <math alttext=3D"iK" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"foo=
tnote10.m6"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=
=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">i=
K</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_i ital=
ic_K</annotation></semantics></math> satisfy <math alttext=3D"-i^{2}=3DK^{2=
}=3D\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(iK}}\right)^{2}=3DiK\mathopen{}\mathclose{=
{\left(iK}}\right)=3D1" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote10.m7"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><msup><mi=
>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=3D</mo><msup><mi>K</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=
=3D</mo><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow></mrow><m=
o>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=3D</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>K</mi><mrow><mi><=
/mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo><mo>=3D</mo=
><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">-i^{2}=3DK^{2}=
=3D\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(iK}}\right)^{2}=3DiK\mathopen{}\mathclose{{=
\left(iK}}\right)=3D1</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-lla=
mapun">- italic_i start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT =3D italic_K =
start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT =3D start_OPEN end_OPEN start_C=
LOSE ( italic_i italic_K end_CLOSE ) start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERS=
CRIPT =3D italic_i italic_K start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_i ital=
ic_K end_CLOSE ) =3D 1</annotation></semantics></math>.
They therefore generate a Clifford algebra isomorphic to the <em class=3D"l=
tx_emph ltx_font_italic">pseudo-quaternions</em>
(Stueckelberg 1960). In a sense,
then, the Hilbert spaces of quantum systems are actually defined not
over the complex numbers alone, but over the pseudo-quaternions, although
<math alttext=3D"K" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote10.=
m8"><semantics><mi>K</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">K</anno=
tation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_K</annotation=
></semantics></math> is not usually used in the definition of observables.<=
/span></span></span></p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: =
none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS4.p7">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">It follows immediately from the dictionary formula (<a c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S3.E31" title=
=3D"In 3.4 Unistochastic processes =E2=80=A3 3 The Stochastic-Quantum Corre=
spondence =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_ref_tag">31</span></a>)
relating <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}=
}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p7.m1=
"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mr=
ow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mro=
w></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma=
\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation><annotation=
 encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=93 start_OPEN end_OPEN start=
_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math> a=
nd <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" c=
lass=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p7.m2"><semantic=
s><mrow><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"=
false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}=
\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_=
U start_OPEN end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 0 end_CLOSE )</annot=
ation></semantics></math>
that every unistochastic transition matrix is <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_fon=
t_italic">doubly stochastic</em>,
or <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">bistochastic</em>, which means th=
at summing over any of its
rows <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">or</em> any of its columns alwa=
ys yields <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S=
3.SS4.p7.m3"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex=
">1</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">1</annotati=
on></semantics></math>:</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"displa=
y: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
