is, in particular, a unitary matrix. Moreover, because the entries
<math alttext=3D"\Sigma_{ij}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S=
3.SS4.p9.m2"><semantics><msub><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><mrow><=
mi>i</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>j</mi></mrow><=
/msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Sigma_{ij}</annotation><a=
nnotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=A3 start_POSTSUBSCR=
IPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math> of =
a permutation matrix <math alttext=3D"\Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D=
"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p9.m3"><semantics><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</=
mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Sigma</annotation><annotatio=
n encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=A3</annotation></semantics>=
</math>
are all <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.=
SS4.p9.m4"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">=
1</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">1</annotation=
></semantics></math>s and <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D=
"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p9.m5"><mn>0</mn></math>s, they are individually inva=
riant when one
computes their modulus-squares, so every permutation matrix is <em class=3D=
"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">also</em>
a unistochastic matrix. It follows that a discrete, deterministic
system whose dynamics is defined by a permutation matrix <math alttext=3D"\=
Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS4.p9.m6"><semantics=
><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/=
x-tex">\Sigma</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">r=
oman_=CE=A3</annotation></semantics></math>
