<p class=3D"ltx_p">which resembles the divisibility condition (<a class=3D"=
ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S2.E6" title=3D"In 2.1=
 Basic definitions =E2=80=A3 2 Indivisible Stochastic Processes =E2=80=A3 T=
he Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">=
6</span></a>).
However, it follows from an elementary theorem of linear algebra that
the inverse of a stochastic matrix can only be stochastic if both
matrices are permutation matrices and, therefore, do not involve
nontrivial probabilities. Hence, the matrix <math alttext=3D"\tilde{\Gamma}=
\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow t^{\prime}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_=
math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS5.p2.m7"><semantics><mrow><mov=
er accent=3D"true"><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mo>~</mo></mover>=
<mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</=
mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{\Gamma}\mathopen{}\mathcl=
ose{{\left(t\leftarrow t^{\prime}}}\right)</annotation><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-llamapun">over~ start_ARG roman_=CE=93 end_ARG start_OPEN=
 end_OPEN start_CLOSE ( italic_t =E2=86=90 italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT =
=E2=80=B2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_CLOSE )</annotation></semantics></math>
defined above is not generically stochastic, so one does not obtain
a genuine form of divisibility.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=
=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
