</semantics></math>, in keeping
with the general definition of state vectors discussed in Subsection&nbsp;<=
a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S3.SS2" tit=
le=3D"3.2 The Hilbert-space representation =E2=80=A3 3 The Stochastic-Quant=
um Correspondence =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3.2</span></a>,
and where the overbar notation denotes complex conjugation.</p><button clas=
s=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding el=
ement</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Remarkably, the right-hand side of (<a class=3D"ltx_ref"=
 href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S3.E43" title=3D"In 3.5 Interf=
erence =E2=80=A3 3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 The Stoc=
hastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">43</spa=
n></a>)
gives the general mathematical formula for quantum interference, despite
the absence of manifestly quantum-theoretic assumptions. One sees
from this analysis that interference is a direct consequence of the
stochastic dynamics not generally being divisible. More precisely,
interference is nothing more than a generic discrepancy between the
<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">actual</em> indivisible stochastic d=
ynamics and a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">heuristic-approximate<=
/em>
divisible stochastic dynamics. Interference encodes the fact that
the underlying stochastic dynamics is indivisible, despite the way
that unitary time-evolution operators look <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_i=
talic">superficially</em> divisible.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" st=
yle=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p6">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">In particular, quantum-mechanical interference does not =
imply that
matter has a physically wavelike nature, contrary to frequent claims
in textbook treatments&nbsp;(Feynman et al. 1965).
Indeed, from the perspective of the present discussion, the notion
that quantum-mechanical interference ever necessitated assigning matter
a physically wavelike quality was merely an unfortunate accident of
history, arising from the fact that many early empirical examples
of interference in quantum systems happened to resemble the behavior
of interfering waves propagating in three-dimensional physical space.</p><b=
utton class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for pr=
eceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p7">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">These historical examples were clearly special cases. <e=
m class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">Multiparticle</em>
systems have Schr=C3=B6dinger waves that propagate through high-dimensional
configuration spaces, as Schr=C3=B6dinger himself noted in his early work
on wave mechanics (Schr=C3=B6dinger 1926).
For more abstract systems, like <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">qubi=
ts</em>, there fail to exist
continuous configuration spaces for Schr=C3=B6dinger waves altogether.</p><=
button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for p=
receding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p8">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">This new way of thinking about quantum-mechanical interf=
erence has
implications for the interpretation of the famous <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx=
_font_italic">double-slit experiment</em>.
Recall that in the double-slit experiment, an emitter sends one particle
at a time toward a wall with two slits in it, and a detection screen
on the other side of the wall records the particle=E2=80=99s eventual landi=
ng
site. In the usual =E2=80=98classical=E2=80=99 description
of the experiment, one asks first which slit the particle enters,
and then, <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">conditioning</em> <em clas=
s=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">on the answer</em>, one then <em class=3D"lt=
x_emph ltx_font_italic">restarts</em>
the dynamics with that slit as the new initial condition. Over many
repetitions of the experiment, the detection screen records a statistical
blend from the landing sites of particles passing through the <em class=3D"=
ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">upper</em>
slit and particles passing through the <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_itali=
c">lower</em> slit. In the case
of quantum-mechanical particles like electrons, however, one instead
finds that the landing sites form a =E2=80=98wavelike=E2=80=99
interference pattern, and the conclusion is supposedly that each particle
is really a Schr=C3=B6dinger wave of some kind or that the particle fails
to go through one slit or the other.<span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footno=
te" id=3D"footnote13"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">13</sup><span class=3D"l=
tx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark=
">13</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">13</span>The exposition by F=
eynman, Leighton, and Sands (1965)
ends up at precisely such a conclusion: =E2=80=9CIt is <em class=3D"ltx_emp=
h ltx_font_italic">not</em> true that
the electrons go <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">either</em> through=
 hole 1 or hole 2.=E2=80=9D [Emphasis
in the original.] This conclusion, however, does not logically follow
from the empirical appearance of interference effects, but also implicitly
depends on the hidden assumption that the behavior of an electron
in a double-slit experiment can be described by divisible dynamics.</span><=
/span></span></p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">=
Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p9">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">According to the approach laid out in this paper, the pa=
rticle always
fundamentally has a single location and is never in both holes simultaneous=
ly.
The final interference pattern on the detection screen is not due
to any purported physical reality of Schr=C3=B6dinger waves, but due to
the generic indivisibility of time evolution for quantum systems.
One cannot divide up the particle=E2=80=99s evolution into, firstly, its tr=
ansit
from the emitter to the slits, and then, secondly, conditioned on
which slit the particle enters, the particle=E2=80=99s transit from the sli=
ts
to the detection screen. The interference that shows up in the double-slit
experiment may be surprising, but that is only because indivisible
stochastic dynamics can be highly unintuitive. In the historical absence
of a sufficiently comprehensive framework for describing indivisible
stochastic dynamics, it was difficult to recognize just how unintuitive
such dynamics could be or what sorts of empirical appearances it
could produce.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;"=
>Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p10">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">In response to this last point, one might suggest that S=
chr=C3=B6dinger
waves nonetheless offer a superior means of explaining why the double-slit
experiment yields the results that it does. Unfortunately, such hopes
are dashed as soon as one considers sending in <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_fo=
nt_italic">two</em> particles
on each run of the experiment. A two-particle system=E2=80=99s Schr=C3=B6di=
nger
wave evolves in a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">six-dimensional</e=
m> configuration space, which
is arguably not more physically transparent than indivisible stochastic
dynamics. Indeed, where are the slits supposed to be <em class=3D"ltx_emph =
ltx_font_italic">located</em>
in this six-dimensional configuration space?</p><button class=3D"sr-only bu=
tton" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS5.p11">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Of course, if one regards the quantum-mechanical particl=
es that make
up matter as arising more fundamentally from underlying <em class=3D"ltx_em=
ph ltx_font_italic">quantum fields</em>,
then the wavelike properties of those quantum fields ensure that particles
of matter have wavelike properties as well and therefore exhibit
a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">wave-particle duality</em>. That s=
aid, there is nothing about
the analysis of the double-slit experiment alone that calls for positing
quantum fields. The necessity of quantum field theory comes from other
theoretical and empirical considerations.<span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_f=
ootnote" id=3D"footnote14"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">14</sup><span class=
=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note=
_mark">14</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">14</span>For a modern m=
otivation, see the textbook by Weinberg (1996).</span></span></span>
One should also keep in mind that quantum fields are conceptually
distinct from Schr=C3=B6dinger waves.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" s=
tyle=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S3.SS6">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">3.6 </span>Implications of inter=
ference</h3><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Repor=
t issue for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS6.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">The fact that interference shows up in a sufficiently ge=
neric stochastic
model means that relative phase factors in state vectors have clear
empirical signatures, even in the absence of the usual axioms of textbook
quantum theory. These empirical manifestations of relative phases
are strong evidence that it should be possible to carry out measurements
on a much wider set of observables than those that are represented
by diagonal matrices in an indivisible stochastic process=E2=80=99s configu=
ration
basis. Indeed, Subsection&nbsp;<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/html/2302.10778v3#S4.SS2" title=3D"4.2 The measurement process =E2=80=A3=
 4 Measurements =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">4.2</span></a> will
show that non-diagonal, self-adjoint matrices will turn out to be
candidate observables as well.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D=
"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS6.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Thinking more broadly, this overall analysis means that =
if one is
given an indivisible stochastic process, then there will generically
be a quantitative discrepancy between the system=E2=80=99s actual behavior=
=E2=80=94as
predicted theoretically or measured empirically=E2=80=94and predictions
made for the system based on a heuristic-approximate divisible or
Markovian approximation to the system=E2=80=99s stochastic dynamics. Again,
this discrepancy is precisely interference.</p><button class=3D"sr-only but=
ton" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS6.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">One way to understand this discrepancy is to note that u=
nder a divisibility
approximation, one can assign definite probabilities to each of the
system=E2=80=99s possible trajectories by iteratively applying transition
matrices, according to the composition law <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen=
{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)=3D\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\=
left(t\leftarrow t^{\prime}}}\right)\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t^{\=
prime}\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline"=
 id=3D"S3.SS6.p3.m1"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal=
">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false=
">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=3D</mo><mi ma=
thvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><m=
o stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup=
></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow=
><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><mo stre=
tchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><anno=
tation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\=
leftarrow 0}}\right)=3D\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow t^{\p=
rime}}}\right)\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t^{\prime}\leftarrow 0}}\r=
ight)</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">roman_=CE=
