ication/x-llamapun">italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT =E2=80=B2 end_POSTSUPERS=
CRIPT</annotation></semantics></math>,
one sees that the interaction with the environment has effectively
eliminated the off-diagonal entries, or <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_ital=
ic">coherences</em>, in the
subject system=E2=80=99s density matrix. This phenomenon is called <em clas=
s=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">decoherence</em>,
and the foregoing analysis makes clear that decoherence is nothing
more than the mundane leakage of correlations into the environment
when viewed through the lens of the Hilbert-space formulation.</p><button c=
lass=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding=
 element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS8.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">This analysis also sheds new light on the meaning of coh=
erences in
density matrices, as well as on <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">supe=
rpositions</em> in state vectors,
where superpositions are related to coherences in the case of a rank-one
density matrix through the formula <math alttext=3D"\rho_{i_{1}i_{2}}\matho=
pen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)=3D\Psi_{i_{1}}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\lef=
t(t}}\right)\overline{\Psi_{i_{2}}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)}"=
 class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS8.p4.m1"><semant=
ics><mrow><mrow><msub><mi>=CF=81</mi><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></msub=
><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn>=
</msub></mrow></msub><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow=
