<p class=3D"ltx_p">so the two subsystems will cease exhibiting what had loo=
ked like
nonlocal stochastic dynamics.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"=
display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS9.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">This analysis precisely captures the quantum-theoretic n=
otion of
<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">entanglement</em>, without any invoc=
ation of a Hilbert-space picture.
Systems that interact with each other start to exhibit what superficially
appears to be a nonlocal kind of stochastic dynamics, even if the
systems are moved far apart in physical space, and decoherence by
the environment effectively causes a breakdown in that apparent dynamical
nonlocality.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">R=
eport issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS9.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Due to the stochastic and non-Markovian nature of the la=
ws in this
new formulation of quantum theory, the precise nature of this apparent
dynamical nonlocality is an extremely subtle matter. Relevant questions
concerning locality and causation will be treated in detail in future
work.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report i=
ssue for preceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_section" id=3D"S4">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">4 </span>Measurements</h2><button c=
lass=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding=
 element</button>
<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S4.SS1">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.1 </span>Emergeables</h3><butt=
on class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for prece=
ding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">The preceding sections have shown that an indivisible st=
ochastic process=E2=80=94that
is, a physical model with kinematics based on a configuration space
and dynamics based on a suitably non-Markovian stochastic law=E2=80=94is
capable of accounting for signature features of quantum theory like
superposition, interference, decoherence, and entanglement. In addition,
the Hilbert-space side of the dictionary (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"http=
s://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S3.E15" title=3D"In 3.1 The dictionary =E2=
=80=A3 3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Qua=
ntum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">15</span></a>)
contains many expressions and equations that are identical to those
found in quantum theory.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"displ=
ay: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">However, an actual quantum system also includes observab=
les beyond
the random variables introduced in Section&nbsp;<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S2" title=3D"2 Indivisible Stochast=
ic Processes =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a>=E2=80=94that
is, beyond the narrow class of observables that are represented by
diagonal matrices. Indeed, the existence of noncommuting observables
represented by self-adjoint matrices that are non-diagonal is another
hallmark feature of quantum theory.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" sty=
le=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Remarkably, an indivisible stochastic process will gener=
ically contain
such observables as well. Specifically, the next subsection will establish
that non-diagonal, self-adjoint matrices represent candidate observables
that naturally satisfy the usual probabilistic rules of quantum theory,
including the Born rule, all without the need to introduce any new
fundamental axioms. In so doing, the analysis ahead will demonstrate
that the dictionary (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/23=
02.10778v3#S3.E15" title=3D"In 3.1 The dictionary =E2=80=A3 3 The Stochasti=
c-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><=
span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">15</span></a>) is not merely a tool
for studying a broad class of stochastic processes, but defines a
comprehensive stochastic-quantum correspondence.</p><button class=3D"sr-onl=
y button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</butt=
on>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">These non-diagonal observables therefore resemble random=
 variables
in some ways but represent emergent patterns in the overall stochastic
dynamics for measurement processes and do not have a transparent
interpretation at the level of the underlying configuration space
<math alttext=3D"\mathcal{C}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S=
4.SS1.p4.m1"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9E=
</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{C}</annotation><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_C</annotation></se=
mantics></math>. These observables will therefore be called <em class=3D"lt=
x_emph ltx_font_italic">emergeables</em>.
This terminology is intended for contrast with the system=E2=80=99s genuine
random variables, which could be called <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_ital=
ic">beables</em>=E2=80=94that
is, =E2=80=98be-ables=E2=80=99=E2=80=94to invoke a
term coined by Bell (1973) to refer to observables
that express how a system can physically <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_ita=
lic">be</em>, ontologically
speaking.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Repo=
rt issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS1.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">There is a sense in which emergeables are not an entirel=
y new idea,
but are similar to emergent physical properties like temperatures
or pressures that likewise do not have a clear meaning at the level
of a system=E2=80=99s fine-grained states. A somewhat more closely related
notion appears in Niels Bohr=E2=80=99s famous reply (Bohr 1935, Bell 1971)
to the <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen parad=
ox</em> (Einstein, Podolsky,
Rosen 1935), in which
Bohr describes emergent observables that show up in measurement interaction=
s.
These sorts of emergent observables also play a key role in the <em class=
=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">de Broglie-Bohm formulation</em>,
or <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">Bohmian mechanics</em> (Bell 1982=
, Daumer et al. 1996),
in which they account for observables other than particle positions.</p><bu=
tton class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for pre=
ceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S4.SS2">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.2 </span>The measurement proce=
ss</h3><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report iss=
ue for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS2.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">With all the requisite conceptual background now in plac=
e, one can
proceed to model the measurement of a generic observable as a physical
process. To start, consider a composite system <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{S}=
\mathcal{D}\mathcal{E}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS2.=
p1.m1"><semantics><mrow><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AE=
</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_=
mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9F</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=
=8B</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=E2=84=B0</mi></mrow><annota=
tion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{S}\mathcal{D}\mathcal{E}</anno=
tation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_S caligr=
aphic_D caligraphic_E</annotation></semantics></math>
consisting of three subsystems that will be called a <em class=3D"ltx_emph =
ltx_font_italic">subject system</em>
<math alttext=3D"\mathcal{S}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S=
4.SS2.p1.m2"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AE=
</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{S}</annotation><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_S</annotation></se=
mantics></math>, a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">measuring device<=
/em> <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{D}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"S4.SS2.p1.m3"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=
=92=9F</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{D}</annotati=
on><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_D</annotatio=
n></semantics></math>, and an
<em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">environment</em> <math alttext=3D"\m=
athcal{E}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS2.p1.m4"><seman=
tics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=E2=84=B0</mi><annotation encod=
ing=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{E}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-llamapun">caligraphic_E</annotation></semantics></math>. Note =
that one of the additional
goals ahead will be to identify the criteria for a subsystem like
<math alttext=3D"\mathcal{D}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S=
4.SS2.p1.m5"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9F=
</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{D}</annotation><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_D</annotation></se=
mantics></math> to be regarded as a genuine measuring device in the
first place.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">R=
eport issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS2.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Focusing momentarily on the subject system <math alttext=
=3D"\mathcal{S}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS2.p2.m1">=
<semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AE</mi><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{S}</annotation><annotation enco=
ding=3D"application/x-llamapun">caligraphic_S</annotation></semantics></mat=
h>, consider
an <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"=
S4.SS2.p2.m2"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0=
.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-t=
ex">N\times N</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">i=
talic_N =C3=97 italic_N</annotation></semantics></math> self-adjoint matrix=
</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue =
for preceding element</button>
