<p class=3D"ltx_p">as follows from any of the standard proofs.</p><button c=
lass=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding=
 element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS5.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">The stochastic-quantum correspondence goes beyond replic=
ating the
uncertainty principle by painting a clearer picture of what the uncertainty
principle physically means. Consider for simplicity the case in which
<math alttext=3D"\tilde{A}=3DA" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D=
"S4.SS5.p2.m1"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>A</mi><mo>~</mo>=
</mover><mo>=3D</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-=
tex">\tilde{A}=3DA</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamap=
un">over~ start_ARG italic_A end_ARG =3D italic_A</annotation></semantics><=
/math> is a random variable, or beable, and <math alttext=3D"\tilde{B}" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p2.m2"><semantics><mover ac=
cent=3D"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation encoding=3D"applicati=
on/x-tex">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llama=
pun">over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></semantics></math> is
an emergeable, in the language of Subsection&nbsp;<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S4.SS1" title=3D"4.1 Emergeables =
=E2=80=A3 4 Measurements =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><=
span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">4.1</span></a>.
Then <math alttext=3D"A" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5=
.p2.m3"><semantics><mi>A</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">A</=
annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_A</annota=
tion></semantics></math> has a direct interpretation solely in terms of the=
 subject
system=E2=80=99s configuration space, whereas <math alttext=3D"\tilde{B}" c=
lass=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p2.m4"><semantics><mover =
accent=3D"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation encoding=3D"applica=
tion/x-tex">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-lla=
mapun">over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></semantics></math> enc=
odes an emergent
pattern in the subject system=E2=80=99s dynamics that can nonetheless show
up in the measurement outcomes of a measuring device.</p><button class=3D"s=
r-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element<=
/button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Suppose that <math alttext=3D"A" class=3D"ltx_Math" disp=
lay=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3.m1"><semantics><mi>A</mi><annotation encodin=
g=3D"application/x-tex">A</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x=
-llamapun">italic_A</annotation></semantics></math> has a definite value or=
 magnitude at some initial
time <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5=
.p3.m2"><mn>0</mn></math>. Then, assuming that <math alttext=3D"A" class=3D=
"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3.m3"><semantics><mi>A</mi><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">A</annotation><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_A</annotation></semantics></math> has no=
 degeneracies in its spectrum,
the subject system must be in a specific configuration with probability
<math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3.m=
4"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">1</annot=
ation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">1</annotation></seman=
tics></math> at the initial time <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" dis=
play=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3.m5"><mn>0</mn></math>. The overall stochast=
ic dynamics will
then lead to uncertainty in the outcome of any measurement of <math alttext=
=3D"\tilde{B}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p3.m6"><s=
emantics><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-llamapun">over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></seman=
tics></math>.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">=
Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p">Suppose that one goes ahead and measures <math alttext=
=3D"\tilde{B}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m1"><s=
emantics><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-llamapun">over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></seman=
tics></math>, so that a definite
measurement outcome emergently shows up in the configuration of a
measuring device at some time <math alttext=3D"t^{\prime}&gt;0" class=3D"lt=
x_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m2"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t=
</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">t^{\prime}&gt;0</annotation><annotation encodin=
g=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT =E2=80=B2 end_P=
OSTSUPERSCRIPT &gt; 0</annotation></semantics></math>. The analysis in Subs=
ection&nbsp;<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v=
3#S4.SS3" title=3D"4.3 Wave-function collapse =E2=80=A3 4 Measurements =E2=
=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_r=
ef_tag">4.3</span></a>
then implies that there is an inevitable disturbance in the subject
system that leads its density matrix to end up effectively as a non-diagona=
l
matrix equal to an eigenprojector of <math alttext=3D"\tilde{B}" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m3"><semantics><mover accent=3D=
"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-te=
x">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">ov=
er~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></semantics></math>. A non-diago=
nal
density matrix signifies that the system is in the midst of an indivisible
stochastic process, as explained in Subsection&nbsp;<a class=3D"ltx_ref" hr=
ef=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2302.10778v3#S3.SS8" title=3D"3.8 Decoherence =
=E2=80=A3 3 The Stochastic-Quantum Correspondence =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-=
Quantum Correspondence"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3.8</span></a>=
.
In the present circumstances, that indivisible stochastic process
is precisely one that would ensure that if <math alttext=3D"\tilde{B}" clas=
s=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m4"><semantics><mover acc=
ent=3D"true"><mi>B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation encoding=3D"applicatio=
n/x-tex">\tilde{B}</annotation><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamap=
un">over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG</annotation></semantics></math> were m=
easured
again shortly after <math alttext=3D"t^{\prime}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m5"><semantics><msup><mi>t</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</m=
o></msup><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t^{\prime}</annotation>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-llamapun">italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCR=
IPT =E2=80=B2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math>, then the=
 measuring device would
obtain the same outcome for <math alttext=3D"\tilde{B}" class=3D"ltx_Math" =
display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS5.p4.m6"><semantics><mover accent=3D"true"><m=
